JAVASCRIPT:

*parseFloat()
The parseFloat() function parses an argument (converting it to a string first if needed) and returns a floating point number.


if (!validateFloat(billAmount.value)) {
        console.log('valid')
    } else {
         console.log('invalid')

    }


HTML:

regexp:
*     [0-9]+\.?[0-9]+

     Explanation: 
          [0-9] : this expression matches digits from [0-9]. 
             +  : it also accepts one or more numbers '123', '000'
             \. : accepts "."
             ?  : zero or one (optional),
          the last two parts of the expression were explained above. 
          which means it accepts any number from 1 to 9 and more. and also decimal numbers if necessary. 